Gemini said
It’s definitely worth optimizing. When you start adding 5 or 6 different files (exports, completions, git-configs, etc.), that if...then block becomes a repetitive eyesore.

Since you're looking for succinctness and scalability, here are the best ways to handle this.

1. The "Loop" Approach (Most Scalable)
Instead of checking every file by name, you can store your file names in a list and loop through them. This keeps the logic in one place.

Bash
for file in aliases functions exports; do
    [ -f "$BASH_CONF_DIR/$file" ] && . "$BASH_CONF_DIR/$file"
done
Why it's better: To add a new file, you just add one word to the list.

The && trick: This is a shorthand for if. It basically says: "If the first part is true, do the second part."

2. The "Function" Approach (Cleanest .bashrc)
If you want your main .bashrc to stay pristine, you can define a helper function at the very top.

Bash
# Define the loader
load_conf() {
    [ -f "$BASH_CONF_DIR/$1" ] && . "$BASH_CONF_DIR/$1"
}

# Use it
load_conf "aliases"
load_conf "functions"
load_conf "secrets"
3. The "Wildcard" Approach (Zero Maintenance)
If you want to never touch your .bashrc again, you can tell Bash to just load everything inside a specific directory.

Bash
if [ -d "$BASH_CONF_DIR/conf.d" ]; then
    for f in "$BASH_CONF_DIR/conf.d/"*; do
        [ -r "$f" ] && . "$f"
    done
fi
Pros: You just drop a new file into the folder and it works instantly.

Cons: Order matters in Bash. If aliases needs something from env, you have to name them like 01-env, 02-aliases to ensure they load in the right sequence.

Comparison Table
Method	Succinctness	Maintenance	Control
Manual (Current)	Low	High (Annoying)	High
Loop	High	Low	High
Function	Medium	Medium	High
Wildcard	Very High	Zero	Low
My Recommendation
Go with the Loop. It strikes the best balance between "less typing" and "knowing exactly what is being loaded."

